2026-03-25 Omar A. Herrera Reyna <0h3rr3r4@gmail.com>

	* configure.ac (AC_INIT): Bumped version to 1.0.4.

	* README: Updated version references to 1.0.4 and documented new
	column-level MAC protection attributes.

	* db.c (cmeMemSecureDBProtect): Implemented the "MAC" column
	protection attribute: for each data row, computes HMAC-SHA-256 of
	the plaintext value (using the per-row salt and orgKey via PBKDF2)
	and stores the 64-hex-char result in the MAC column of the data
	table.  Also implemented the "MACProtected" attribute: re-reads
	the already-encrypted value from the in-memory DB and stores its
	HMAC in the MACProtected column.  Both use cmeHMACByteString()
	with cmeDefaultMACAlg ("sha256").

	* db.c (cmeMemSecureDBUnprotect): Implemented verification for
	both new column attributes.  For "MAC": re-reads the decrypted
	value from the DB after the "protect" unprotect step has run,
	recomputes HMAC, and compares against the stored MAC value;
	returns error 23 on mismatch.  For "MACProtected": uses the
	encrypted-value snapshot (memData) taken at function entry,
	recomputes HMAC, and compares against the stored MACProtected
	value; returns error 25 on mismatch.  Either mismatch signals
	data integrity failure.

	* function_tests.c (testCSV): Added a test case for the
	"protect"/"MAC"/"MACProtected" attribute set: calls
	cmeCSVFileToSecureDB with those three attributes in sequence,
	then retrieves via cmeSecureDBToMemDB and prints the decrypted
	result.  All 10 rows pass MAC and MACProtected verification.

	The expected column meta-table ordering for correct operation is
	protect → MAC → MACProtected.  With this ordering, during protect
	MAC uses the pre-encryption memData snapshot, and MACProtected
	queries the DB after encryption.  During unprotect the reverse
	holds: MAC queries the DB after decryption, and MACProtected uses
	the pre-decryption snapshot.

